body: can you post a sample warning. where are these coming from?

See below. There's one depracation warning; some from numpy complaining about empty/0-length arrays; and one about comparing objects (column labels) that can't be compared.

```

  warnings.warn("Degrees of freedom <= 0 for slice", RuntimeWarning)
C:\Python34\lib\site-packages\numpy\lib\nanfunctions.py:1059: RuntimeWarning: Degrees of freedom <= 0 for slice.
  warnings.warn("Degrees of freedom <= 0 for slice.", RuntimeWarning)

ok

ok

  "incomparable objects" % e, RuntimeWarning)
c:\Users\seth\Documents\github\pandas\build\lib.win-amd64-3.4\pandas\core\index.py:1218: RuntimeWarning: unorderable types: float() < str(), sort order is undefined for incomparable objects
  "incomparable objects" % e, RuntimeWarning)
ok

test_rolling_apply (pandas.stats.tests.test_moments.TestMoments) ... C:\Python34\lib\site-packages\numpy\core\_methods.py:59: RuntimeWarning: Mean of empty slice.
  warnings.warn("Mean of empty slice.", RuntimeWarning)
ok
```

I thought I was also getting a warning in test_rolling_consistency(), though don't see one there now, so maybe it doesn't need the warnings-suppression code. Would have expected a numpy warning here about empty/0-length arrays, given that get one in test_expanding_consistency().

These are on the numpy_master build? (e.g. the one at the bottom of travis). 

hmm, maybe see what is causing them and may need to not pass certain things to numpy (e.g. if then len is 0), they are getting more strict esp in 1.9

Afraid I'm not sure where they are in Travis. The output I provided is from when I run:

```
C:\Python34\scripts\nosetests --verbosity=3 build\lib.win-amd64-3.4\pandas\stats
```

I think it might be a bit of a pain to test all the Pandas functions with empty/0-length objects, while (b) ensuring that we never pass an empty/0-length object to numpy. Probably doable, but would likely make the testing code more awkward.
Just updated the commit to leave test_rolling_consistency() unchanged, as it doesn't seem to be producing a warning.
